Part I - Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Ashley Muthoni¶

Introduction¶

This dataset details data regarding various variables related to loans from the identification details of the borrowers to the various loan amounts, the status of the loan, borrower rate and other related characteristics.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset had 113,937 loan observations spread across 81 variables. Most of them were numeric in nature with some like the ListingCategory listed from a scale of 0 to 20 to represent its string observation of reasons listed for applying for loans.

However, I performed some transformation on the expansive column variables by selecting the key columns I think will be of great importance for our analysis which truncated the dataset to 23 columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in the dataset are the factors affecting the outcome of a loan especially the amount of money issued for the loan and its monthly payment for a prospective and/or current borrower.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I deduce of importance in this dataset are the quantitative variables such as the BorrowerRate, LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment with those having higher loans remit higher monthly fees. Qualitative ones such as the employment status also influences the outcome as those that are in stable employment or self employed are more likely to take higher loans.

Univariate Exploration¶

I will start by looking at the key variables of interest with regards to loan, the BorrowerRate or the Interest rate.

How does the interest rate charged on a loan and expected lender yield for investors appear?¶

The Annual percentage rates charged on loans seems to have a have a very strong similar relationship with the expected annual yield that lenders can expect from their investment.

However, on closer analysis of its peaks we see that borrowers pay a higher interest(0.36) and eventual total cost of credit for their loans than inveestors receive for their investment(0.31). This can create a margin for Prosper to profit from.

    '''Define quick function to plot a bar chart'''
    Dataframe.plot.barh(figsize=size)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 13)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 13)
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 13)
    plt.show()

The scheduled monthly loan payments has a long-tailed distribution with positive-skewness. Most of the payments are on the lower priced end. When plotted on the log-scale, it appears unimodal with majority of the payments ranging between 100 and 800.

The original amount of money originated for the loan had a moderate right-skew which when transformed on a log scale showed sharp spikes at approximately every 1000 ie. 4k, 5k, 6k which is fairly unimodal.

Further investigation of this key variable will be seen in relation to other key metrics.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The monthly loan payments took a biased range values towards the right which necessitated a log transformation that made it look fairly unimodal.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When investigating the listing categories, I had to transform the numeric values to string values for better interpretation. To improve the clarity of analysis I filtered those above the mean value count to view top 5 categories.

Bivariate Exploration¶

To start off with, I want to look at the pairwise correlations present between features in the data.

How does BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, LenderYield, LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment relate pairwise?¶

In [20]:
numeric_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'BorrowerRate', 'LenderYield', 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'MonthlyLoanPayment']
In [21]:
# plot matrix: sample 3000 loans so that plots are clearer and they render faster
loan_sample = df.sample(n = 3000, replace = False)

g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);
In [22]:
sb.heatmap(loan_sample[numeric_vars].corr(), cmap = 'Blues', annot =True, fmt = '.4f');

As expected, the BorrowerRate, BorrowerAPR and LenderYield dimensions are all highly correlated with one another. This is a good indication of favorable terms of taking loans as there are minor differences in the rates charged particularly between the interests rate and APR. This means there is little additional fees and time charged over the life of the loans compared to the interest rate. The inverse relation to LoanOriginalAmount and MonthlyLoanPayment is a moderate negative correlation.

LoanOriginalAmount and MonthlyLoanPayment has strong positive correlation as previously hypotheisized. This is to be expected as huge loan amounts requirelarger portions of money to financeon a monthly basis. As confirming the hypothesis, they'll be of key importance for the subsequent analyses.

Next is to look at how they correlate with various categorical variables.

How has the loan amount progressed over the years?¶

# Define chart to plot line chart

def chart(Dataframe, x_values, x_label, y_values, y_label, colour):
    '''quick function to compute the average loan disbursed for over time in a line plot'''
    Dataframe.plot(x=x_values, y=y_values, color=colour, figsize=(10,6), grid=True)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize = 13)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize = 13)
    plt.show();
In [25]:
df_loans = df.groupby('Year')['LoanOriginalAmount'].mean()
In [26]:
chart(df_loans, 'Year', 'Year', 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'Loan Amount($)', 'blue')

From the trend observed above, Prosper progressively increased the amount of money disbursed for its loan particlarly from the year 2009. This can be due to more thorough record keeping being done for loans post July 2009 to include variables like EstimatedEffectiveYield. This is not of utter importance for the analysis.

How does the average loan amount differ across different employment statuses?¶

Despite full-time employed borrowers accounting for the greatest proportion as previously observed, employed and self-employed borrowers received the greatest average loan amount. This is interesting as self employed borrowers are not that many but receive favorable loan outcomes together with their employed counterparts.

As expected, the more the number of investors funding a loan, the higher the loan is as observed from the strong positive correlation.

It's interesting to note a moderate negative correlation for the lender yield investors can expect from their investment annually against the number of investors. This means more investors funding a loan does not necessarily translate to higher returns when interest rates and fees are compounded annually.

It will be exciting to see how these variables come together in the subsequent analysis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Using a random sample of the loans from the dataset, it was evident that key original loan amounts and the monthly loan amounts had a strong linear relationship as hypothesized. This will further be explored in the next section.

Categories such as the employment status of the borrowers and the status of already issued loans also influenced the amount of money disbursed as loans. Most of them are in good standing in terms of employment and have completed their payments.

Although an increase in amount of loans disbursed over years after 2009 was observed, there are comprehensive records kept for those years to include other variables like the Prosper Rating which we dropped and hence which slightly biases the data. Thus, it is good just for our knowledge and not analysis.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

It was surprising to see that the lender yield and investors that funded the loan were not strongly positively corelated as expected. One expected that the more the number of investors funding a loan, the higher the investment outcomes which was not observed. This might result from other underlying factors in the institution that affects the structure and outcome of the loan.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

For this investigation of the multivariate exploration, the strong positive relation between the loan amount and monthly payment towards it remained consistent across the categoric variables. This is especially true for borrowers with more favorable statuses as majority confidently qualified for loans they could afford within a regulated timeframe. Longer periods of 60 months seem most favorable for servicing a loan to completion. Higher and lower loan amounts have similar relationships in relation to the loan term but varies across the different statuses.Their monthly payments also have similar relations.

One does not need many investors to fund their loan as higher lender yield attracted more investment and thus borrowers could get more money loaned out.This is key for Prosper as a lender to keep both investors and customers appeased.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It is not surprising that with the backing of documentation to verify ones income, loan outcomes were improved. However, not all income ranges had standard middle half ranges with majority having upper outliers beyond the whiskers to show favoarable loan amounts issued.

Conclusions¶

  • The primary focus was on the amount of money issued at the time of origination. This variable is heavily influenced by not only the borrowers' circumstances but the lender as well.Steps have been taken to explore major variables like the monthly loan payment with variables like the loan status amongst borrowers.

  • A good lender does not have a stark contrast between the APR and interest rate as seen that would eventually make the loan expensive for borrowers.

  • A history of having good standing regardless of the reason for applying for the loan greatly improves the loan outcome. As seen with debt consolidation being the top reason borrowers apply for loans, that will be of particular importance for future refinancing of other debts through loans.

  • It is important to note that as much as investors can fund a loan, not every loan ends up being beneficial to the investor as some end up in default with those unable to pay and others are completely charged-off. This means that the loan is a liability and cannot benefit the investor.

  • From the visualizations above, we can conclude that although the borrower's factors play the greatest role in determining the outcome of a loan, the kind of backing the lender has also influences how they structure the loan they offer.
